00:41:46.070 --> 00:41:48.020
when I have kids, I want
to do the same thing.

00:41:48.020 --> 00:41:50.920
So it'll be neat to see
the grandkids doing that.

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:53.000
ASHLEY CHANG: So
the coolest part

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:55.260
for me hearing about
the Donut Council--

00:41:55.260 --> 00:41:59.000
and why I wanted to talk about
it today-- is it's not just

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:01.400
go eat donuts with Dad.

00:42:01.400 --> 00:42:03.812
You talk about real lessons.

00:42:03.812 --> 00:42:05.270
Can you share a
little bit of that?

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:06.103
DARON ROBERTS: Yeah.

00:42:06.103 --> 00:42:08.380
So we talk through
current events.

00:42:08.380 --> 00:42:09.770
I usually pick
one current event,

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:13.730
and then I'll pick
one character trait.

00:42:13.730 --> 00:42:17.390
And so a couple of weeks
ago, it was gratitude.

00:42:17.390 --> 00:42:20.900
And we talked about the
value of saying thank you.

00:42:20.900 --> 00:42:23.110
And I'll have them
kind of think about,

00:42:23.110 --> 00:42:26.420
hey, when was the last
time you said thank you?

00:42:26.420 --> 00:42:28.730
Sydney-- you could tell Sydney
kind of runs the house--

00:42:28.730 --> 00:42:33.080
Sidney said she got an extra
slice of pizza at school,

00:42:33.080 --> 00:42:35.189
and she told the lady at
the cafeteria thank you.

00:42:35.189 --> 00:42:37.230
I was like, well, how did
you get an extra slice?

00:42:37.230 --> 00:42:39.961
She goes, oh, well, she knows
I really like this cheese

00:42:39.961 --> 00:42:42.460
that they don't normally have,
and she gave me an extra one.

00:42:42.460 --> 00:42:43.310
ASHLEY CHANG: It's not dry.

00:42:43.310 --> 00:42:44.476
DARON ROBERTS: It's not dry.

00:42:44.476 --> 00:42:46.250
She's very particular
about her food.

00:42:46.250 --> 00:42:48.140
And I said, well, how
do you think she felt?

00:42:48.140 --> 00:42:50.750
She goes, she gave me
a big smile, right?

00:42:50.750 --> 00:42:53.900
So we talk about how there
are these things called

00:42:53.900 --> 00:42:58.700
soft skills that people talk
about that's completely off.

00:42:58.700 --> 00:43:00.134
They're hard.

00:43:00.134 --> 00:43:01.550
And these are the
skills that will

00:43:01.550 --> 00:43:05.000
get you fired,
hired, governments

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:06.680
fall, countries fall--

00:43:06.680 --> 00:43:08.717
like just truth and integrity.

00:43:08.717 --> 00:43:10.550
So they're very important,
and they're hard.

00:43:10.550 --> 00:43:13.741
And we have to be very
intentional about talking

00:43:13.741 --> 00:43:14.240
about them.

00:43:19.940 --> 00:43:23.030
Now they have their own topics.

00:43:23.030 --> 00:43:24.530
They're starting to bring them.

00:43:24.530 --> 00:43:28.550
Hey, can we talk about
movies and how we

00:43:28.550 --> 00:43:30.979
can get more time on the iPad?

00:43:30.979 --> 00:43:33.270
I'm like, no, it doesn't
really fit in with the scheme.

00:43:33.270 --> 00:43:33.690
ASHLEY CHANG: Veto power.

00:43:33.690 --> 00:43:34.900
DARON ROBERTS: Veto
power, done, right?

00:43:34.900 --> 00:43:35.560
ASHLEY CHANG: Not a soft skill.

00:43:35.560 --> 00:43:36.150
DARON ROBERTS: Yeah,
not a soft skill.

00:43:36.150 --> 00:43:37.340
It doesn't fit.

00:43:37.340 --> 00:43:41.120
So it's been a blast.

00:43:41.120 --> 00:43:44.180
ASHLEY CHANG: You are
teaching students and athletes

00:43:44.180 --> 00:43:45.811
how to take risks.

00:43:45.811 --> 00:43:47.810
Are you starting to teach
that to your children?

00:43:47.810 --> 00:43:49.850
And if so, how are
you doing that?

00:43:49.850 --> 00:43:51.830
DARON ROBERTS:
Yeah, so I'm going

00:43:51.830 --> 00:43:54.080
to start this year
actually to kind of going

00:43:54.080 --> 00:43:55.970
through the rejection resume.

00:43:55.970 --> 00:43:57.730
I going to start
broadcasting when I get

00:43:57.730 --> 00:43:58.730
turned down from things.

